51. THE MS. volume, now presented for the first time in extenso, has long been known to liturgica] writers, and has been frequently quoted by them under the title of‘The Leofric Missal.' It is so called from its having been the property 01 Leofric¹ first bishop of Exeter, and by him presented to Exeter Cathedral. Its liturgical interest lies in the fact that it is one 01 the only three surviving Missals known to have been used in the English Church during the Anglo-Saxon period, its companion volumes being the Missal 01 Robert of Jumieges‚ Archbishop of Canterbury‚ written in the first half of the eleventh century, and now in the Public Library at Rouen, [MS.Y.6], and the ‘Rede Boke 01 Darbye,’ written in the second half of the eleventh century, now in the Library of Corpus ChristinCollege, Cambridge ².
